<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-744-813  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 744 813.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  July 10 1989 v10 n27 p9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telco loses appeal in RICO case. (Northwestern Bell Telephone Co.,andO;Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Larussa, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Supreme Court rules that the Racketeer Influenced andCorrupt Organizations Act (RICO) can be used in a lawsuit chargingNorthwestern Bell Telephone Co with attempted bribery of stateofficials.andP;  Business groups opposed to the ruling argue that RICOwas not intended to extend to isolated instances of criminalconduct by legitimate businesses.andP;  RICO, they argue, pertains onlyto activities related directly to organized crime.andP;  The SupremeCourt said that Congress had intended the law to cover a widerange of criminal activity and rejected the argument that a singleinstance can never for the basis of a RICO charge.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Northwestern Bell Telephone Co. (cases).andO;Statute:   Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (cases).andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesUnited States. Supreme CourtTelephone CompaniesCourt Cases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>